===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|heroun|lang=enm}}, {{term|heiron|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno}} {{term|heiron|lang=xno}}, from Old Dutch {{term||heigero|lang=odt}} (compare Middle Dutch {{term|heiger|lang=dum}}), from {{proto|Germanic|haigrô|lang=en}} (compare {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|häger|lang=sv}}), metathesis of {{proto|Germanic|title=|hraigrô|lang=en}} (compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|hragra|hrāgra|lang=ang}}, Dutch {{term|reiger|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Reiher|lang=de}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)kreik-||(s)kreig-|to screech, creak|lang=en}} (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|crëyr|lang=cy}} ‘heron’, Ancient Greek {{term||krízein}} ‘to creak’).

